The 50 Gi offers a 185 grain solid copper hollowpoint at 1,200 FPS, a 230 Grain Solid Copper Hollowpoint at 1,000 FPS, a 275 Jacketed Hollwopoint at 875 FPS or a 300 Grain Jacketed FLat Point at 700 FPS. It is more powerfull than a 45 acp but these low pressure loads recoil the same or less than 45 loads.

This LNIB unfired rifle is a Thompson Center Icon chambered for 30TC (a .308 length cartridge that produces ballistics similar to those of a 30-06). title: For Sale:  Russian 1895 7.62 Nagant Pistol. "Complete Package"
postcontent:
I have a very fine Russian 1895 7.62 Nagant Pistol for sale, it comes with its original holster, cleaning rod, lanyard, Nagant Pistol tool, users manual, it has a clean shinny bore, plus 5 full boxes of 109gr ammo, which is its original ammo used.

Now there is PRVI AMMO and it is only 98gr which is the latest ammo found for this pistol on line, this ammo makes a popping sound when used, but it is OK for plunking.

This is a real fine piece of history, there will come a day when this pistol will be a rare collectors item, especially in the excellent condition as this one is. There are pistols like mine for sale on line the only problem is they have the name of the suppler stamped across the frame, makes it look ugly. 

The Nagant Revolver is a seven-shot, gas-seal revolver designed and produced by Belgian industrialist Léon Nagant for the Russian Empire.

The Nagant was chambered for a proprietary cartridge 7.62, and featured an unusual "gas-seal" system, in which the cylinder moved forward when the gun was cocked, to close the gap between the cylinder and the barrel, providing a boost to the muzzle velocity of the fired projectile to be suppressed at 1000fps (an unusual ability for a revolver designed in 1895). 

If you would like to take a closer look and buy this Russian 1895 7.62 Nagant Pistol, call REDACTED or reply by e-mail.

The two pictures are stock photos, the pistol you will receive is exactly the same if not better.
The picture of the ammo is the way it comes from the arsenal, one box fits into the pouch on the holster.

Thank you for viewing my listing.

title: For Sale:  Mosin Nagant 91/30 and 1,000 rounds of 54r for sale
postcontent:
I've got a 1925 hex receiver, Mosin Nagant for sale. No synthetic stock or scope mounts. Comes with the standard tool kit, oil can, sling, and bayonet. Rifling is strong, hasn't been counter bored. I've cleaned off most of the cosmoline, but after 20 rounds or so, you'll notice it to start bubbling out of the stock from the heat.

Along with the rifle, I have about 1,000 rounds of 54r. 
400 Rounds are the regular FMJ surplus, still in the brown paper.
About 67rounds of Silver Bear soft points, still in their box.
Finally, about 600 rounds of Czech "low recoil" rounds, info here: http://7.62x54r.net/MosinID/MosinAmmo013.htm
It's really fun stuff, basically it makes your Mosin feel like a .22. It's great for anyone who likes shooting, especially kids. 

Basically I'm asking $100 for the rifle and $0.20 a round. I'd like to sell the rifle and ammo together, so I'm not lugging around one or the other. Even if you just throw the rifle out, it's still only $0.30 a round. 

I'm in Austin and will meet anywhere within 30 minutes or so. If you want to meet on a range, I'd prefer Lonestar over Reds, but I will go to either. I;m going to require a valid TX Driver's License at the time of sale.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Smith & Wesson Model 457
postcontent:
I have a Smith & Wesson Model 457 with five factory magazines and a S&W box (not original to the gun) that I would like to either sell or trade. The gun itself has a good bore, a little wear on the finish from use, and is a traditional DA/SA with a left side, slide mounted, hammer drop safety. It does have an exposed hammer that is factory flush with the rear of the slide for carry and the first double action shoot. It also has a magazine safety, so the gun will not fire with the magazine removed ala the Browning Hi-Power. It has an aluminium frame for lighter weight. Capacity is 7+1. 

Overall this is a fine concealed carry (or open carry) gun in the proven .45 ACP caliber. Built to the same standards as the larger 3rd generation Smith & Wesson .45s, this gun will feed any type of cartridge design. The sights are a 3 dot arrangement and are easy to pick up for fast shooting. While it has a shorter barrel, I was able to keep a beer can moving out to about 20 yards from an off hand position.
